        <section xml:id="second-order-linear-nonhom">
        <title>Solution Technique 6: Non-homogeneous Second Order ODEs</title>
        <p>
            This note gives a useful technique for solving second-order constant-coefficient ODEs that are not homogeneous. That is, we wish to solve
            <men xml:id="second_non_hom" >
                ax'' + bx' + cx = F(t),
            </men>
            where the function <m>F(t)</m> is nonzero. Often, <m>F(t)</m> corresponds to some external force (not from the spring or damper).
        </p>
    <p>
    It turns out the the technique is nothing more than the <xref ref="u_p-u_h-method" /> and/or <xref ref="undetermined-coefficients"/>, but for second-order equations.
    </p>
        <subsection xml:id="2ndundetermined-coefficients">
          <title>The Method of Undetermined Coefficients</title>

        <theorem xml:id="second-order-linear-solutions">
            <title>Form of Solutions to Second-Order Linear ODEs</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The general solution to the ODE <xref ref="second_non_hom"/> is
                <me>
                    x(t) = x_h(t) + x_p(t)
                </me>
                where <m>x_h(t)</m> is the general solution to the homogeneous first-order ODE
                <men xml:id="2ndhom_aux" >
                    ax'' + bx' + cx = 0
                </men>
                and <m>x_p(t)</m> is any particular solution to <xref ref="second_non_hom"/> you may be able to find.                                
                </p>
            </statement>
        </theorem>
        <proof>
            <p>
                Let <m>x(t)</m> be an arbitrary solution to <xref ref="second_non_hom"/>. Consider the difference <m>x(t) - x_p(t)</m>. Observe that this is a solution to <xref ref="2ndhom_aux"/>. This means <m>x(t)</m> has the form indicated by the theorem.
            </p>
        </proof>
        <algorithm xml:id="undetermined-coefficients2">
            <title>The Method of Undetermined Coefficients</title>
            <p>
                To solve <xref ref="second_non_hom"/>, proceed as follows:
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Solve <xref ref="2ndhom_aux"/> using previously learned technique. Call the general solution to this equation <m>x_h(t)</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Guess a solution <m>x_p(t)</m> to <xref ref="second_non_hom"/> of the same general form as <m>F(t)</m> according to <xref ref="guess-table"/>. If <m>F(t)</m> is a linear combination of functions with forms in the table, make a guess for each term in the linear combination and combine at the end. If your initial guess for <m>x_p(t)</m> is a solution to <xref ref="2ndhom_aux"/>, multiply by a power of <m>t</m> so that it is no longer a solution to <xref ref="2ndhom_aux"/>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Solve for unknown coefficients by substituting <m>x_p(t)</m> into <xref ref="second_non_hom"/>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Form the general solution and solve for coefficients using initial conditions.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
            </p>
        </algorithm>

        <table xml:id="guess-table">
            <title>Good Guesses for Undetermined Coefficients</title>
            <tabular>
                <row header="yes">
                    <cell><m>F(t)</m></cell> <cell>Guess for <m>x_p(t)</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Polynomial of degree <m>n</m></cell> <cell>Polynomial of degree <m>n</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>ae^{kt}</m></cell> <cell><m>Ae^{kt}</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>a\cos(\omega t)</m></cell> <cell><m>A\cos(\omega t) + B\sin(\omega t)</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>a\sin(\omega t)</m></cell> <cell><m>A\cos(\omega t) + B\sin(\omega t)</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>ae^{kt}\cos(\omega t)</m></cell> <cell><m>Ae^{kt}\cos(\omega t) + Be^{kt}\sin(\omega t)</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>\vdots</m></cell> <cell><m>\vdots</m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>



        
            
